<h2>
    What is HTML?
</h2>
<p>
    <b>HyperText Markup Language</b>, or HTML, is a <b>syntax</b> for the structure of a website.     
    It contains elements which are the building blocks. Inside each element 
    is its inner HTML or text that is displayed to the browser.
    Tags contain the innerHTML and start and end with brackets <code>&lt;like this&gt;</code>. 
    Most tags have end tags as well: tags that mark the end of an element and 
    are differentiated with forward slashes <code>&lt;/like this&gt;</code> . 
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-html">&lt;!-- Create p tag --&gt;
&lt;p&gt; inner HTML Goes Here &lt;p&gt;
</code></pre>

<h2 class="display-6">
    Tags
</h2>

        <p>
            Tags are the essential building blocks of 
            any HTML document. They start and end with angle brackets:
            <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> and have an end tag with angle brackets, but
            with a forward slash, to indicate the end
            of the content: <code>&lt;/a&gt;</code>. Between those two 
            tags comes the text content of the tag. Inside the start tag, there
            are attributes which are variables given a value with the <code>=</code> operator.
        </p>
    
<pre><code class="lang-html">&lt;a href="/"&gt;Anchor Tag&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>
<pre><code class="lang-html">&lt;p&gt;Paragraph Tag&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>
    

<h2 class="display-6">
    Attributes
</h2>


<p>
    Between the start and end tags comes the text then inside the start tag, there
    are attributes which are variables given a value with the <code>=</code> operator.
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-html">@HTMLExample2</code></pre>    
<p>
    In the example above, the p element has a style attribute that sets the color 
    of that paragraph to red. 
</p>
<p>
    Different tags have different attributes, like how 
    buttons have the onclick attribute and paragraphs do not. 
</p>

